natural problem: The equation $y=-16t^2+22t+45$ describes the height (in feet) of a ball thrown upwards at $22$ feet per second from $45$ feet above the ground. Find the time (in seconds) when the ball will hit the ground. Express your answer as a common fraction.
natural solution: The equation $y=-16t^2+22t+45$ can be rewritten as $y=(8t+9)(-2t+5)$. Because $t$ needs to be positive, set $-2t+5=0$ to represent the point where the ball reaches the ground.

a_0.formal problem:
theorem
fixes t :: real and y :: "real \<Rightarrow> real"
assumes h0 : "\<forall> t. y t = -16 * t powr 2 + 22 * t + 45"
and h1 : "y t = 0"
shows  "t = 5 / 2"
a_0.formal solution:
(* ### Problem
 The equation $y=-16t^2+22t+45$ describes the height (in feet) of a ball thrown upwards at $22$ feet per second from $45$ feet above the ground. Find the time (in seconds) when the ball will hit the ground. Express your answer as a common fraction. The final Answer is \frac{5}{2}
 ### Proof
 The equation $y=-16t^2+22t+45$ can be rewritten as $y=(8t+9)(-2t+5)$. Because $t$ needs to be positive, set $-2t+5=0$ to represent the point where the ball reaches the ground.
 Therefore: \begin{align} -2t+5&=0\\ -2t&=-5\\ 2t&=5\\ t&=\boxed{\frac{5}{2}} \end{align}
 *)

 proof-
